Dat 402 Project 1: Lillian Tretheway¶

Predicting Obesity¶

Obesity is one of the largest preventable diseases in the United States and can cause many other issues such as cardiovascular diseases and cancer. There are many attributes that increase a person's chance of being obese such as family history and diet. We want to predict if someone will be obese based off of the list of attributes in the study because obesity is a common and detrimental disease. Being able to predict whether someone is high-risk for obesity and identify what factors are most influential can help people make lifestyle changes and improve their health.

Import Dataset¶

https://archive.ics.uci.edu/dataset/544/estimation+of+obesity+levels+based+on+eating+habits+and+physical+condition¶

Predicting weight class based on other factors. 5 weight classes range from underweight to level 3 obesity¶

There are 16 variables in this dataset consisting of different variable types such as binary, contiuous, categorical, and integer.

Independent variables: The first feature is gender which is labeled as male/female. Age, Height, and Weight are continous variables that are set to the individual's value for each variable. Familiy_history_with_overweigh is a yes/no variable that reflects whether or not the individual has a family member who suffers from obesity. FAVC is the answer to the yes/no question of "Do you eat high caloric food frequently?" and FAVC is the answer to the question "Do you usually eat vegetables in your meals?". The variable NCP is the number of meals eaten per day and CAEC is if the individual eats in between meals. SMOKE is the binary variable of whether or not the individual smokes. CH20 is how much water drinken per day, SCC is whether or not the individual monitors calories per day, and FAF is how often the individual participates in physical activity. TUE is how often the individual uses electronics such as video games, television, etc. CALC is how often the individual drinks alcohol and MTRANS is the form of transportation that the individual normally uses.

Dependent variabels: NObeyesdad is the categorical variable of all the different class ranges of obesity.

Multicollinearity is when some of the independent variables are highly correlated to eachother. A general correlation value to show that there is multicollinearity is if the correlation coefficient is greater than 0.8 which we do not have in our results.

Encoding Training Data and Continued Analysis¶

Several predictors are based on categorical data, so encoding some variables was necessary.

OrdinalEncoder¶

'Snacks' and 'Alcohol' columns needed to be encoded with the sklearn OrdinalEncoder because these columns have a clear meaningful order. OrdinalEncoder works by assigning a numeric value from 1 to the number of unique categorical instances. If no order is explicitly given, it will assume alphabetically. In this case, a specific order was necessary. By encoding these categories as numbers in this manner, their ranking is preserved without assuming any specific distance between them, which is important for capturing the ordinal relationships in the model.

The target variable was dropped for the remainder of analysis for organizational purposes.

In [483]:

Dummy Variables:¶

Dummy variables were used to encode other categorical data. Dummy variables create binary columns for each unique categorical instances in a column. In this case, the drop_first function was used, so the number of columns added in place of the original columns is n-1, where n is the number of unique categorical instances. This approach was used for all other categorical variables that have no inherant rank, such as 'Yes' and 'No' or 'Female' and 'Male'.

After encoding with dummy variables, column names change, some new columns are present, and previously categorical data is stored in a binary format.

Correlation matrix of all variables¶

Now that we have all of the variables, we can do another correlation matrix with all of our variables. To check for multicolinearity, we want to make sure that no values are near or greater than 0.8. Since our highest correlation coefficient is 0.62 for Height and Gender_Male (where 0 is female and 1 is male), there is a very low chance of having multicollinearity.

Height and Gender_Male have a somewhat positive correlation of 0.62. This makes sense because men tend to be taller than females. It appears that Height tends to have the most correlations between other variables such as the variables stated in the previous correlation matrix. Height is also slightly positively correlated to Fam_Hist_yes with a coefficient of 0.25. Age is somewhat negatively correlated to Transport_Type_Public_Transport with a coefficient of -0.55. Age and tech_time are slightly negatively correlated with a coefficient of -0.3 which makes sense because younger people are more likely to use more technology such as video games.

To ensure multicollinearity won't be a signficant issue, the VIF was checked for each variable. VIF stands for "Variance Inflation Factorr" and quantified how much of the variance of regression coefficient is inflated due to multicollienarity. VIF values greater than 5 indicate that may be some effect on model performance due to redundant information. VIF values greater than 10 indicate severe mutlicollienarity and should be dealt with accordingly. Below shows that no variables are of concern for multicollinearity.

In [488]:
import pandas as pd
import statsmodels.api as sm
from statsmodels.stats.outliers_influence import variance_inflation_factor

# Ensure your DataFrame is numeric
obesity_train_numeric = obesity_train.apply(pd.to_numeric)

# Add a constant column for the intercept
obesity_train_vif = sm.add_constant(obesity_train_numeric)

# Calculate VIF for each predictor variable (skipping the constant column)
vif_data = pd.DataFrame()
vif_data["Feature"] = obesity_train_vif.columns[1:]  # Skip the constant column
vif_data["VIF"] = [variance_inflation_factor(obesity_train_vif.values, i) 
                   for i in range(1, obesity_train_vif.shape[1])]  # Start from index 1

print(vif_data)

Model 1: Multinomial Naive Bayes¶

The first model tested is Multinomial Naive Bayes. Due to most of the data being categorical, this model is ideal. Multinomial Naive Bayes works best with discrete or categorical data. Numeric data can be acceptable when transformed with binning or frequency counts, so that is what was done. Binning was used for both Age and Height to categorized as 'Young', 'Middle-aged' or 'Old' for age and 'Short', 'Average', or 'Tall' for height.

MNB models also assume feature independence and a multinomial distribution. Since data is or is transformed into categorical or discrete data, scaling is not necessary.

Pass 1: Validation Accuracy = 0.37¶

The results are not optimal for this model.

  • Precision - Precision measures the proporation of true positive predications among all positives predictions. The best precision score is for class 2.0, or 'Overweight_Level_I' which indicated 71% correctness when predicting class 2.0. Many other classes are fairly close but there is quite a bit of variance still.
  • Recall - Recall measures the proporation of true positives predictions among actual positive instances. For 'Obesity_Type_III' the model correctly identified and caught 98% of actual instances. Large variances is recall are present with class 3.0 only being 13%.
  • F1-score - This is the harmonic mean, or the balance between precision and recall where 1 is perfect precision and recall and 0 is worst possible performace. The differing values show varying efficiency of precision and recall that errs on the ineffective side for most.
  • Support - Support shows the actaul occurances of the instance in the validation set. All appear balanced and returned similar metrics, so this does not raise significant concern.
  • Overfitting - Test and train accuracy are not significantly different, to there is no imminent concern of overfitting.

def plot_confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred, title='Confusion Matrix'):
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred)
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues', 
                xticklabels=np.unique(y), 
                yticklabels=np.unique(y))
    plt.title(title)
    plt.ylabel('Actual')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.show()

Model 2: Logistic Regression¶

The second model is Logistic Regression. Logistic Regression is usually used for binary target variables, so the solver type was set to 'lbfgs' to handle the multiple classes. 'lbfgs' stands for Limited-memory Broyden-Fletcher-Goldfarb-Shanno method which is more efficient and equipt to handle multi-class logisitc regression problems.

Train, Test, and Validation sets:¶

In addition to the training and test set, this time a validation set was added to verify results and how the model is generalizing results.

In [498]:
obesity_train_scale = obesity_train.copy()

y = obesity_test

X_train, X_val, y_train, y_val = train_test_split(X_train_val, y_train_val, test_size=0.25, random_state=42)  # 0.25 * 0.8 = 0.2 of total data for validation

def plot_confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred, title='Confusion Matrix'):
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred)
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues', 
                xticklabels=np.unique(y), 
                yticklabels=np.unique(y))
    plt.title(title)
    plt.ylabel('Actual')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.show()

Model 3: Random Forest Model¶

The third model chosen is a Random Forest model. A Random Forest model is a type of ensemble learning method used for classification and regression tasks. It works by creating a large number of decision trees during training and then aggregating their predictions to improve accuracy and control overfitting. Again, test, validation, and training sets were used to verify results.

In [504]:

Hyperparameter Tuning¶

  • The results above suggested potentiall overfitting, so hyperparameter tuning is necessary to optimize the model.
  • n_estimators - This is the number of decision tree used inside the Random Forest. Results may change as this increases or decreases.
  • max_depth - This controls the depth of the decision trees. Specifying 'None' allows them to grow without constraint, which poses the risk of overfitting and also the risk of capturing noise. Specifiying a max depth helps balance model complexity with generalization.
  • min_samples_split - This parameter defines the minimum number of samples required to split an internal node, and can be used to prevent the model from learning overly specific patterns that may skew results.
  • min_samples_leaf - This also helps prevent the model from learning overly specific patterns by specifying that a leaf must have more than a certain number of instances, which helps improve generalization.
In [510]:
param_grid_rf = {
    'n_estimators': [100, 200, 300, 500],
    'max_depth': [None, 10, 20, 30, 40],
    'min_samples_split': [2, 5, 10],
    'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2, 4]
}

grid_search_rf = GridSearchCV(estimator=RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42), 
                               param_grid=param_grid_rf, 
                               cv=3, 
                               scoring='accuracy')

grid_search_rf.fit(X_train, y_train)

print("Best parameters for Random Forest:", grid_search_rf.best_params_)

Best parameters for Random Forest: {'max_depth': None, 'min_samples_leaf': 1, 'min_samples_split': 2, 'n_estimators': 300}
